    "last_updated": "2026-04-03",
    "excerpt": "\"Arkin\" is one of two Aramaic piyyutim read by some Ashkenazi communities at the beginning of the Torah reading on the first day of Shavuot (the other being the Aqdamut). The piyyut makes reference to an important legend featuring Mosheh experiencing an ascent in which he must wrest the Torah from angelic entities that are averse to parting with it, or loathe to giving it up, to humanity. Introducing the piyyut she translated in <em>Jewish Aramaic Poetry from Late Antiquity</em> (Brill: 2018), Dr. Laura Lieber writes, \"This [Shavuot] poem dramatizes neither the content of revelation, as other poems here do, nor the season of its giving, as the story of Ruth does. Instead, our poet imagines God’s summoning of Moses to the heavens to receive the Torah atop Mount Sinai. God’s voice is most prominent here, although the angels also speak; Moses, however, keeps silent, and the poet depicts him with anything but aggression and bravado. The poet crafts a scene that recreates the tension of the imagined encounter: God repeatedly reassures Moses, who fears angelic aggression, but the angels also express fear of Moses, who is here depicted as having horns, which God encourages Moses to use in self-defense.\"",
    "content": "<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"font-size: 1.2em;\">\n&#8220;Arלin&#8221; is one of two Aramaic piyyutim read by some Ashkenazi communities at the beginning of the Torah reading on the first day of Shavuot (the other being the Aqdamut). The piyyut makes reference to an important legend featuring Mosheh experiencing an ascent in which he must wrest the Torah from angelic entities that are averse to parting with it, or loathe to giving it up, to humanity. Introducing the piyyut she translated in <em><a href=\"https://brill.com/display/title/22965?language=en\">Jewish Aramaic Poetry from Late Antiquity: Translations and Commentaries</a></em> (Brill: 2018),<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_1');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_1');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_1\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[1]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_1\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Find &#8220;10. Moses is Summoned to the Summit (SABM 11),&#8221; pp. 40–42.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_1').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_1', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> Dr. Laura Lieber writes, &#8220;This [Shavuot] poem dramatizes neither the content of revelation, as other poems here do, nor the season of its giving, as the story of Ruth does. Instead, our poet imagines God’s summoning of Moses to the heavens to receive the Torah atop Mount Sinai. God’s voice is most prominent here, although the angels also speak; Moses, however, keeps silent, and the poet depicts him with anything but aggression and bravado. The poet crafts a scene that recreates the tension of the imagined encounter: God repeatedly reassures Moses, who fears angelic aggression, but the angels also express fear of Moses, who is here depicted as having horns, which God encourages Moses to use in self-defense.&#8221;\n</div>\n<hr />\n<table style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" class=\"draggable toggleable-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th id=\"x\" style=\"text-align: right;\">Source (Aramaic)</th>\n<th style=\"text-align: left;\">Translation (English)</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">א</span>רכין יוי שמיא לסיני<br />\nואמר למשה מהימני תא סוק׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ב</span>ני פלטין לא יבהלונך<br />\nדנצח יתהון סבך מן רישא׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"divine-referent\">The Lord</span> brought down to Sinai the heavens <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nAnd said to Moses: “My faithful one! Come, ascend!<br />\n“My courtiers<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_2');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_2');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_2\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[2]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_2\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Lit., “The sons of (My) palace.”&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_2').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_2', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> shall not make you tremble <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“For your ancestor defeated them long ago.\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ג</span>ומרין דאתון הוה נוריה דנמרד<br />\nולא יכיל למכוי רגלוי דסבך׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ד</span>ביק לית בך נורא דמלאכי<br />\nדעמך אשא אכלא אשא׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n“An oven (full) of coals did Nimrod kindle<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_3');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_3');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_3\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[3]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_3\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Lit., “was Nimrod’s flame.”&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_3').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_3', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“But he was unable to singe the feet of your ancestor<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_4');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_4');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_4\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[4]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_4\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> I.e., Abraham, as in Bereshit Rabbah 38:11 (361-364).&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_4').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_4', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script><br />\n“Neither shall angelic flame cling to you <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“For with you is the fire of <span class=\"divine-referent\">the Consuming Fire</span><span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_5');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_5');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_5\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[5]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_5\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Deuteronomy 4:24 describes <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> as a “consuming fire.” In b. Yoma 21b, “the fire that consumes fire” is identified as <span class=\"divine-referent\">the Shekhinah</span>.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_5').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_5', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ה</span>א אנא מלביש לך פורפירין דידי<br />\nדלית גבר אחרן דתקרב לותך׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ו</span>קבעית קרני הודא והדרא ברישך<br />\nדאי קריב מלאכא תנגשיניה בהון׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n“Indeed, I shall clothe you in My royal purple garment <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“So that no other may approach you<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_6');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_6');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_6\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[6]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_6\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> On the motif of <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> casting <span class=\"divine-referent\">His</span> mantle over Moses to protect him from the angels, see Shemot Rabbah 42:4 (70b) and b. Shabbat 88b.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_6').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_6', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script><br />\n“And I have placed horns of glory and splendor upon your head <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“Should an angel approach you, you should gore him with them!<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_7');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_7');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_7\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[7]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_7\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> That is, Moses’ famous “horns”—in the original biblical context, “rays of light” (Exod 34:35)—here serve a defensive purpose.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_7').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_7', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ז</span>עירא לא תהוי באנפך משה<br />\nדלית את ידע מה חיבתך עלי׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ח</span>י אנא וקיים דיברית איקונך<br />\nעד דלית שכלילית רומא ומכא׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n“Do not consider yourself unimportant in your own eyes, Moses; <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“As you do not know how dear you are to Me.<br />\n“As I live and endure I created your image <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“Before I had completed the upper and lower worlds.&#8221;<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_8');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_8');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_8\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[8]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_8\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\">  The motif of an “image” (איקון) of Moses created prior to the world is novel, but it may draw upon the tradition that <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> created the world for the sake of Moses; see Bereshit Rabbah 1:4 (7). The image of Jacob, however, also mentioned in line 30 below, is an aggadic commonplace; see, e.g., Bereshit Rabbah 12:9 (107).&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_8').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_8', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ט</span>ירוני מרומא קמו להון תמהין<br />\nדי אכסנאה הכא מנן הוא׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">י</span>ה יהיב רישו לבשרא למקרב הכא<br />\nומן כדין אנן אפרופסין׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\nThe guardians of the heavens stood, amazed <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“This stranger here! Whence has he come?<br />\n“<span class=\"divine-referent\">Yah</span> gave His permission for mortal flesh to approach here?! <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“Now we are purposeless!”<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_9');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_9');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_9\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[9]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_9\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> 26 The final word of this stich (אפרופסין) is difficult. The <a href=\"https://cah.cn.huc.edu/\">Comprehensive Aramaic Lexicon</a> (CAL) follows <em>Shirat Bene Ma&#8217;arava</em>’s suggestion that it is a Greek loanword (πρόφασις, pretext, excuse), but Sokoloff leaves it untranslated in <em>A Dictionary of Jewish Palestinian Aramaic of the Byzantine Period</em> (2017), p. 48.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_9').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_9', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">כ</span>ד חמון מלאכיא דעני כדין להון<br />\nדי אכסנאה אנא מהודע לכון׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ל</span>ענותנותא איתקרי משה<br />\nרעוהון דבניי מהימנא דביתי׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\nAs soon as the angels saw (Moses), <span class=\"divine-referent\">He</span> responded to them thus:<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_10');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_10');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_10\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[10]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_10\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> A more direct translation yields, “When the angels saw that <span class=\"divine-referent\">He</span> was answering them thus,” but the sense is difficult and the text may be slightly corrupt.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_10').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_10', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“This<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_11');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_11');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_11\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[11]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_11\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> The translation follows <em>Shirat Bene Ma&#8217;arava</em> in reading דין in place of די on the basis of another manuscript.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_11').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_11', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> stranger, let Me introduce (him) to you:<br />\n“He is the humble one<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_12');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_12');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_12\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[12]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_12\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> This line is translated in keeping with Num 3:12, “Now the man, Moses, was very humble.” This requires a slight emendation of the Aramaic text (ענוונא instead of ענותנותא), which reads “out of humility, he is called Moses.”&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_12').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_12', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> known as Moses, <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“My children’s shepherd, the faithful one of My house.&#8221;\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">מ</span>כון שמיא ורמת ארעא<br />\nואשכח קאים בין חיותא<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">נ</span>עו מלאכין לקביל אופנין<br />\nכד חמון למשה קריב לערפליא׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\nThe heavens descended and the earth rose up <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nAnd he appeared, standing among the Ḥayyot<br />\nThe angels trembled in front of the Ofanim<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_13');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_13');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_13\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[13]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_13\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> The Ḥayyot and Ofanim are two classes of angelic beings.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_13').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_13', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nWhen they saw Moses approach the dark cloud<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_14');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_14');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_14\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[14]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_14\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Exod 20:18, “And Moses drew near into the dark cloud where <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> was.”&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_14').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_14', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ש</span>ערתא דגופיה קמו להון כחדא<br />\nדאיקונין דיעקב הוא מזדקף לקיבליה׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ע</span>ול וקרב לך רעוהון דבנוי<br />\nצוח מן כרסייה מלאכא׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\nThe hair on his body all stood on end <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nFor the visage of Jacob loomed<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_15');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_15');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_15\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[15]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_15\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Lit., “stood upright,” perhaps suggesting an imposing visual presence.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_15').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_15', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> before him<br />\n“Enter and come close, O shepherd of My children!” <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nThe angel called from <span class=\"divine-referent\">His</span> throne.<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_16');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_16');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_16\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[16]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_16\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> The angel functions as a kind of divine herald.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_16').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_16', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">פ</span>סול לך לוחין [מן] סמפרינון<br />\nמן כרסייה דמלכא חייא׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">צ</span>היל הוה ליביה דמשה וחדי<br />\nדהוה רחמנא אפילוגוס דידיה׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n“Hew for yourself (two) tablets<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_17');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_17');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_17\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[17]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_17\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> See Exod 34:1 (and Deut 10:1), where in the aftermath of the golden calf episode <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> commands Moses to write a second set of tablets.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_17').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_17', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> of sapphire, <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“From the throne of <span class=\"divine-referent\">the Living King</span>”<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_18');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_18');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_18\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[18]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_18\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> In Ezek 1:26, <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span>’s throne has “the appearance of sapphire.” The poem seems to assume that the original Ten Commandments were carved on stone taken from the heavenly throne.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_18').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_18', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script><br />\nExultant was the heart of Moses, and he rejoiced <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nFor <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> was merciful and <span class=\"divine-referent\">the Merciful One</span> was his advocate<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_19');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_19');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_19\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[19]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_19\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> The translation reflects the variant adopted in ShBM, which is interpreted there as a Greek loanword that refers to a counselor for the defense, a derivative of the verb ἀπολογέομαι.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_19').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_19', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ק</span>ריבו מלאכיא קדם כרסייה דקיריס<br />\nואמרין בבעו לא ישלט בן<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ר</span>ישא דכיפא בחוטריה תבר<br />\nואנן קשיין ליה למנגשא׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\nThe angels drew close to the throne of <span class=\"divine-referent\">the Lord</span><span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_20');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_20');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_20\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[20]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_20\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Greek loanword, from χύριος.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_20').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_20', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\nAnd said, “Please! Let him not rule over us;<br />\n“The top of the stone with his staff he shattered, <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“But we would be difficult for him to gore.”<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_21');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_21');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_21\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[21]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_21\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> The angels here seem to draw an analogy between themselves and the rock at Massah and Meribah (Exod 17:1-7), noting Moses’ reputation for striking against whatever hinders him; the language harks back to the third stanza, where Moses’ horns are described in terms of self-defense. In Shemot Rabbah 41:7 (6gb–7oa), Moses does in fact attack—with <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span>&#8216;s assistance—the angels of wrath, who seek to prevent him from acquiring the Torah. See Michael Fishbane, <em>The Exegetical Imagination: On Jewish Thought and Theology</em> (Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1998), 199n16.&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_21').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_21', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"liturgy\" lang=\"jpa-Hebr\" style=\"text-align: right;\">\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ש</span>די אמר ליה לא תדחל משה<br />\nדמימרי יהא לך בסעדך׃<br />\n<span class=\"acrostic\">ת</span>יסב אוריתא ותיתוב לך בשלם<br />\nדלא אשכחית בנביאי כוותך׃\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align:top;\">\n<div class=\"english\" lang=\"eng-Latn\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n<span class=\"divine-referent\">The Almighty</span> said to him, “Fear not, Moses,<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_22');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference__1('footnote_plugin_reference__1_22');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_22\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[22]</sup></a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_22\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\"> Poem 13, line 41, is nearly identical: “<span class=\"divine-referent\">The Almighty</span> said to him, “Do not fear, lad? (טליא)!”&nbsp;</span></span><script type=\"text/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_22').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text__1_22', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'center right', relative: true, offset: [0, 0], });</script> <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“For My word shall be your help;<br />\n“Take the Torah and return in peace <span class=\"acrostic\">&nbsp;</span><br />\n“For I have not found among My prophets another like you.”\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<hr />\n<p>This is &#8220;Arkin Hashem Shemaya l&#8217;Sinai,&#8221; an Aramaic piyyut from late Antiquity by an unknown author. The English translation was made by Dr. Laura Lieber as published in <em>Jewish Aramaic Poetry from Late Antiquity: Translations and Commentaries</em> (Brill: 2018), &#8220;10. Moses is Summoned to the Summit (SABM 11),&#8221; on pages 40–42. That translation was made against the critical text offered in <em>Shirat Bene Ma&#8217;arava: Jewish Palestinian Aramaic from Antiquity</em> [Hebrew], edited and translated by Joseph Yahalom and Michael Sokoloff (Jerusalem: Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities, 1999). Our transcription was made against the digital text shared from the <a href=\"https://cal.huc.edu/get_a_chapter.php?file=53420&#038;sub=011&#038;cset=H\">Comprehensive Aramaic Lexicon</a>, derived from the text published in <em>Shirat Bene Ma&#8217;arava</em>. </p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<div class=\"speaker-mute footnotes_reference_container\"> <div class=\"footnote_container_prepare\"><p><span role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_reference_container_label pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container__1();\">Notes</span><span role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_reference_container_collapse_button\" style=\"display: none;; display: none;\" onclick=\"footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container__1();\"></span></p></div> <div id=\"footnote_references_container__1\" style=\"\"><table class=\"footnotes_table footnote-reference-container\"><caption class=\"accessibility\">Notes</caption> <tbody> \r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_1\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_1');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >1</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Find &#8220;10. Moses is Summoned to the Summit (SABM 11),&#8221; pp. 40–42.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_2\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_2');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >2</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Lit., “The sons of (My) palace.”</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_3\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_3');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >3</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Lit., “was Nimrod’s flame.”</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_4\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_4');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >4</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">I.e., Abraham, as in Bereshit Rabbah 38:11 (361-364).</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_5\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_5');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >5</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Deuteronomy 4:24 describes <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> as a “consuming fire.” In b. Yoma 21b, “the fire that consumes fire” is identified as <span class=\"divine-referent\">the Shekhinah</span>.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_6\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_6');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >6</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">On the motif of <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> casting <span class=\"divine-referent\">His</span> mantle over Moses to protect him from the angels, see Shemot Rabbah 42:4 (70b) and b. Shabbat 88b.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_7\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_7');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >7</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">That is, Moses’ famous “horns”—in the original biblical context, “rays of light” (Exod 34:35)—here serve a defensive purpose.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_8\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_8');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >8</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\"> The motif of an “image” (איקון) of Moses created prior to the world is novel, but it may draw upon the tradition that <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> created the world for the sake of Moses; see Bereshit Rabbah 1:4 (7). The image of Jacob, however, also mentioned in line 30 below, is an aggadic commonplace; see, e.g., Bereshit Rabbah 12:9 (107).</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_9\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_9');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >9</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">26 The final word of this stich (אפרופסין) is difficult. The <a href=\"https://cah.cn.huc.edu/\">Comprehensive Aramaic Lexicon</a> (CAL) follows <em>Shirat Bene Ma&#8217;arava</em>’s suggestion that it is a Greek loanword (πρόφασις, pretext, excuse), but Sokoloff leaves it untranslated in <em>A Dictionary of Jewish Palestinian Aramaic of the Byzantine Period</em> (2017), p. 48.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_10\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_10');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >10</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">A more direct translation yields, “When the angels saw that <span class=\"divine-referent\">He</span> was answering them thus,” but the sense is difficult and the text may be slightly corrupt.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_11\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_11');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >11</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">The translation follows <em>Shirat Bene Ma&#8217;arava</em> in reading דין in place of די on the basis of another manuscript.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_12\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_12');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >12</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">This line is translated in keeping with Num 3:12, “Now the man, Moses, was very humble.” This requires a slight emendation of the Aramaic text (ענוונא instead of ענותנותא), which reads “out of humility, he is called Moses.”</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_13\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_13');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >13</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">The Ḥayyot and Ofanim are two classes of angelic beings.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_14\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_14');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >14</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Exod 20:18, “And Moses drew near into the dark cloud where <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> was.”</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_15\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_15');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >15</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Lit., “stood upright,” perhaps suggesting an imposing visual presence.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_16\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_16');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >16</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">The angel functions as a kind of divine herald.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_17\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_17');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >17</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">See Exod 34:1 (and Deut 10:1), where in the aftermath of the golden calf episode <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span> commands Moses to write a second set of tablets.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_18\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_18');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >18</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">In Ezek 1:26, <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span>’s throne has “the appearance of sapphire.” The poem seems to assume that the original Ten Commandments were carved on stone taken from the heavenly throne.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_19\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_19');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >19</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">The translation reflects the variant adopted in ShBM, which is interpreted there as a Greek loanword that refers to a counselor for the defense, a derivative of the verb ἀπολογέομαι.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_20\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_20');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >20</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Greek loanword, from χύριος.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_21\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_21');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >21</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">The angels here seem to draw an analogy between themselves and the rock at Massah and Meribah (Exod 17:1-7), noting Moses’ reputation for striking against whatever hinders him; the language harks back to the third stanza, where Moses’ horns are described in terms of self-defense. In Shemot Rabbah 41:7 (6gb–7oa), Moses does in fact attack—with <span class=\"divine-referent\">God</span>&#8216;s assistance—the angels of wrath, who seek to prevent him from acquiring the Torah. See Michael Fishbane, <em>The Exegetical Imagination: On Jewish Thought and Theology</em> (Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1998), 199n16.</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr class=\"footnotes_plugin_reference_row\"> <th scope=\"row\" id=\"footnote_plugin_reference__1_22\" class=\"footnote_plugin_index pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToAnchor__1('footnote_plugin_tooltip__1_22');\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_plugin_link\" >22</a></th> <td class=\"footnote_plugin_text\">Poem 13, line 41, is nearly identical: “<span class=\"divine-referent\">The Almighty</span> said to him, “Do not fear, lad? (טליא)!”</td></tr>\r\n\r\n </tbody> </table> </div></div><script type=\"text/javascript\"> function footnote_expand_reference_container__1() { jQuery('#footnote_references_container__1').show(); jQuery('#footnote_reference_container_collapse_button__1').text('−'); } function footnote_collapse_reference_container__1() { jQuery('#footnote_references_container__1').hide(); jQuery('#footnote_reference_container_collapse_button__1').text('+'); } function footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container__1() { if (jQuery('#footnote_references_container__1').is(':hidden')) { footnote_expand_reference_container__1(); } else { footnote_collapse_reference_container__1(); } } function footnote_moveToReference__1(p_str_TargetID) { footnote_expand_reference_container__1(); var l_obj_Target = jQuery('#' + p_str_TargetID); if (l_obj_Target.length) { jQuery( 'html, body' ).delay( 0 ); jQuery('html, body').animate({ scrollTop: l_obj_Target.offset().top - window.innerHeight * 0.2 }, 380); } } function footnote_moveToAnchor__1(p_str_TargetID) { footnote_expand_reference_container__1(); var l_obj_Target = jQuery('#' + p_str_TargetID); if (l_obj_Target.length) { jQuery( 'html, body' ).delay( 0 ); jQuery('html, body').animate({ scrollTop: l_obj_Target.offset().top - window.innerHeight * 0.2 }, 380); } }</script>",
